: [Placeholder for course content] - Table showing: CPM Killer | What It Does | How to Avoid It ## 2.2 The First Three Lines Rule - Why the first 3 lines decide 80% of your CPM - How Meta reads and scores your opening - Examples of high vs low performing openings ## 2.3 Hook Structures Meta Prefers - Framework for creating algorithm-friendly hooks - Native vs promotional tone comparison - 20+ plug-and-play hook templates (structure) # SECTION 3: DETAILED CLICK-BY-CLICK IMPLEMENTATION SOPs ## SOP #1: CONDUCTING YOUR CPM AUDIT Detailed table with columns: - Step # | Action to Take | Where to Click | Expected Input | Expected Output | Success Indicator | Troubleshooting Steps should include: 1. Access Meta Ads Manager 2. Navigate to Campaign View 3. Add CPM Column to Reports 4. Export Current CPM Data 5. Identify High CPM Campaigns 6. Document Current Performance Baseline ## SOP #2: ANALYZING YOUR CURRENT AD COPY Detailed table format covering: 1. Select ad to analyze 2. Review first 3 lines 3. Check for CPM Killers 4. Score engagement potential 5. Identify improvement opportunities 6. Document findings ## SOP #3: REWRITING AD COPY FOR LOWER CPM Detailed table format covering: 1. Apply First Three Lines Rule 2. Implement native tone 3. Remove CPM Killers 4. Add Invisible Engagement Cues 5. Test hook structures 6. Delay offer presentation (strategic positioning) 7. Finalize copy 8. Document changes ## SOP #4: LAUNCHING YOUR OPTIMIZED AD Detailed table covering: 1. Create new ad in Ads Manager 2. Keep same targeting 3. Keep same offer 4. Keep same landing page 5. Keep same budget 6. Insert new copy 7. Launch campaign 8. Set monitoring alerts ## SOP #5: MONITORING & OPTIMIZATION CYCLE Detailed table covering: 1. Wait 24-48 hours for data 2. Check CPM metrics 3. Compare to baseline 4. Analyze CTR changes 5. Track conversion impact 6. Calculate ROI improvement 7. Document learnings 8. Scale or iterate # SECTION 4: OPTIMIZATION STRATEGIES FROM TOP 1% ADVERTISERS ## 4.1 Copy 